  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Prince of Henan
  author: Park Ui-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Emperor bestows his sacred mandate,
    And you, noble lord, aid the flourishing realm.
    Your name shines bright as sun and moon,
    Your deeds illuminate all heaven and earth.

    The jade long hidden in transformation's vault,
    The timber select from the craftsman's grove—
    Rare indeed is such a sage of our age,
    Who graces the great man's gate.

    Like the great fish that rises when rain comes,
    Like the phoenix that soars on the wind's breath,
    Your crystalline character rivals jade trees,
    Your fragrant virtue carries the orchid's perfume.

    In service you master all subtle response,
    In verse you compose with wondrous skill.
    The Way appears in a single glance,
    And when minds accord, words become needless.

    From this moment begins our bond,
    A pledge we make to never forget,
    Throughout the long years ahead.
  footnotes:
    - The 'sacred mandate' (休命) references the Confucian concept of Heaven's mandate legitimizing virtuous rule.
    - The jade and timber imagery draws on classical symbols of inner worth waiting to be discovered and cultivated.
    - The phoenix and great fish are traditional symbols of worthy officials rising to prominence.
    - The poem employs the classical conceit that true understanding transcends language.
